Title: Layla
Album: Layla And Other Assorted Love Songs (Remastered 2010)
Comment:
Too many good options for this round, but I think this is best because my dad would get to pause and tell the story. Did you know that Eric Clapton was in love with George Harrison’s wife Pattie Boyd, this song was written about her, Boyd later divorced Harrison and married Clapton? And Harrison even attended the wedding?
I bet you did know but so does my dad and he’d love to tell you the story.

Title: Just
Comment: Do I get a pass for having been pedantic about it in a Hard Times article as well? Hope so. Anyway, (a) it doesn't rip off "Smells Like Teen Spirit", and (b) that rising guitar line after the initial acoustic guitar chords is an octatonic (or diminished) scale (tone-semitone-tone-semitone-tone-semitone-tone), which ought to sound like insufferable jazz-prog bullshit but doesn't. Also it fits over the opening chords, which BLOWS MY MIND. (See also - the whole-tone scale in "Banana Co.")

Title: Stuck In The Middle With You
Comment: When I was maybe 12, I was on a trip with my family to visit relatives, and this song came on the radio early in the trip. My mom insisted it was by Bob Dylan. I spent the entire two hours arguing that it was not. This was pre-smartphone so we had to wait until we arrived to confirm (probably via AOL on a dial-up modem). I was right! I am 35 and I still love to tell my mom how right I was. Also, fun to ask where you know this song from, then point out it was prominently used in Reservoir Dogs.

Title: A Better Place
Comment: Everyone (and by that I mean other people who think about this album) thinks about this album wrong. It’s not just an Afrofuturist sci-fi hip hop/noise album, but it’s also a critique of afrofuturism’s take on fugitivity being rooted in a specific destination that doesn’t exist. The bells on this track, which are a clear reference to early FM synthesis, illustrate that perfectly. In line with buchla, the bells represent a sense of possibility in embracing the unknown and the openness of the void

Title: The Secret Life Of Plants

Comment: My dad used to lay in the middle of the floor, put headphones in, and listen to this song while loudly singing along in the most off-key way imaginable because he (obviously) couldn't hear himself. Every single other family member in the household was present and like actively walking around him. ???

Title: You Never Even Called Me by My Name
Comment:
This song was the song that helped me get more in touch with my partner's family. I'm not a huge country guy, and if I'm being honest I don't know if I ever even heard of David Allan Coe before dating them. 

But every time there was a big event, party, wedding, holiday, graduation, their big ass family would always at some point in the night blast this song from some hidden speaker they'd always have, and everyone would drunkenly sing their hearts out to it. Just great memories surrounding it.

Title: Vodkasodaburg
Comment: 6ish years ago I saw this band on tour but didn't really know them. A couple months after I was visiting a friends house when this song came up on house Spotify shuffle. I stupidly asked "is this birdsong?" One roommate laughed and corrected me it's "birdcloud." I told them I only recognized it from a live show and that got us talking about music. Cut to: As of three weeks ago they are now my fiancee. I guess I should get bands names wrong more often.

Title: Jackson Cannery
Comment: I used to spend every summer in the deep woods of Maine. My parents would let me drive on dirt roads when I turned 13 to learn. Around that time we also got a CD player in our car for the first time. There were only a handful of CDs my parents and I could agree on and this was one of them. I have such a firm memory of driving for the first time down a windy dirt road, passing logging trucks, and singing “I got Jackson Cannery” at full volume. It was the wild Wild West up there.
